csimile Transmission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many fax machines there are in (a) his Department and (b) his Department's non-departmental public bodies (NDPBs); and how many fax machines his Department and its NDPBs have purchased and at what cost since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","214661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155961","Department of Health","false","2014-11-24","<p>We have ensured that carers are central to our proposals for care and support reform. The provisions in the Care Act focus on the carer in their own right. For the first time, local authorities have a duty to meet carers’ eligible support needs and to consider the impact of their caring responsibilities when undertaking an assessment.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We have also ensured that young carers and parent carers of disabled children are supported. Through the provisions of the Children and Families Act, their assessments will be on the same footing as adults caring for adults.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We have provided £400 million to the National Health Service over four years from 2011 for carers to have breaks from their caring responsibilities. The 2015-16 tranche of this funding (£130 million) will be part of the Better Care Fund.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>On 30 October 2014, the Government published an updated action plan for the national Carers Strategy, setting out progress since 2010 and priorities for the next two years through to 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Carers are also central to the work that NHS England is leading to improve the quality of life of people with long term conditions. Their action plan <em>NHS England’s Commitment to Carers</em> includes a series of commitments around eight priorities, including raising the profile of carers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-11-24T17:24:22.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155961/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155961/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps he has taken to improve the support provided to carers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","214632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155962","Department of Health","false","2014-11-20","<p>In making prescribing decisions, a clinician should first and foremost consider a patient’s individual clinical needs and choose the medicine best fitted to meet those needs, whether the medicine is licensed, off-label or unlicensed. Clinicians will also take a range of other information into account including advice from sources such as the British National Formulary, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence and any local prescribing policies.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Guidance to clinicians from both the General Medical Council and the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency sets out a clear hierarchy for the licensing status of medicines, which supports them in making these decisions. In treating their patients, clinicians should first consider using a licensed medicine within its licensed indication but if that will not meet their patient’s needs they can consider a licensed medicine outside its licensed indication and only if that is not suitable should they consider using a medicine that is not licensed. They must discuss the options with the patient and explain the reasons for their choice including the significance of the licensing status of the medicine.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-11-20T12:51:31.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155962/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155962/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Prescription Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether a licence for a treatment indication makes it more likely to be prescribed for that indication in (a) off-label and (b) unlicensed indication.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","214607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155963","Department of Health","false","2014-11-24","<p>Matters concerning the Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG) are for NHS England. We understand that NHS England is currently considering whether it will publish the minutes of CPAG meetings.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-11-24T15:38:02.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155963/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155963/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Levodopa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the minutes of Clinical Priorities Advisory Group meetings relating to Duodopa.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","214681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155964","Department of Health","false","2014-11-20","<p>Departmental officials have had a number of discussions with NHS England which have included this issue, as well as discussions with other stakeholders. We are committed to supporting clinicians in incorporating the most up to date and robust evidence into patient care.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-11-20T17:07:26.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155964/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155964/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Drugs: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on what dates since July 2014 he has discussed with NHS England the use of off-patent drugs for new indications; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","214697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155965","Department of Health","false","2014-11-24","<p>We have had no such discussions.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-11-24T15:33:38.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155965/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155965/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Levodopa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with (a) NHS England and (b) external stakeholders on access to Duodopa for people with Parkinson's disease.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","214679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155966","Department of Health","false","2014-11-24","<p>NHS England has advised that it has received two complaints relating to individual funding requests for Parkinson’s disease medicines in the last 12 months.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2014-11-24T15:26:03.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155966/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155966/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many complaints NHS England received regarding individual funding requests for Parkinson's disease medication in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","214680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155967","Department of Health","false","2014-11-20","<p>The Government continues to carefully consider all issues relevant to the introduction of standardised packaging of tobacco products including any evidence from Australia. The Government has not yet made a final decision on whether to introduce standardised packaging of tobacco products.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-20T14:56:46.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155967/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155967/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Tobacco: Australia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effects of standardised packaging of tobacco in Australia.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","214703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155968","Home Office","false","2014-11-27","<p>Passport applications from British citizens overseas are made online and dealt with in the United Kingdom. There are no plans to forward material which is not relevant to the passport process when responding to passport applicants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-27T16:34:50.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155968/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155968/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Electoral Register: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy that passport offices should publicise the Electoral Commission's campaign to increase the number of UK citizens living abroad who are registered to vote in UK elections when people apply for passports.","false","Biography information for Sir Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","The Cotswolds","Geoffrey Clifton-Brown","214692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155969","Home Office","false","2014-12-17","<p>As an incentive to promote good behaviour and thereby improve the effectiveness of the training programme the Army proposed to allow the trainees some very limited unsupervised access to the local amenities. These proposals were discussed across Government (including the Home Office) prior to implementation. <br><br>The Home Office requested that the Army liaise closely with Cambridgeshire Police on the monitoring of such visits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-12-17T18:13:48.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155969/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155969/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Armed Forces: Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what role her Department had in formulating the walking out policy covering Libyan recruits being trained at Bassingbourn barracks; and what role (a) her Department and (b) the police had in monitoring that policy.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","214678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155970","Home Office","false","2014-11-20","<p>There have been no discussions between the Secretary of State and Ministers from the Scottish Government on the contract for the operation of the 101 non-emergency number.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-11-20T14:40:26.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155970/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155970/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","101 Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with Ministers in the Scottish Government on the contract for the operation of the 101 non-emergency number.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","214698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155971","Home Office","false","2014-11-21","<p>Consumer research undertaken by the Department following the launch of the 101 non-emergency service showed that the majority of respondents felt that the 15 pence call charge was reasonable.<br><br>Research by Ofcom shows that a small fixed charge does not deter people from calling the service and reduces the likelihood of it being used inappropriately. <br><br>The Crime Survey for England and Wales shows that 51% of the public are aware of 101. Awareness and use of the number have increased steadily since 2011, when 30% of the public were aware of it. Calls almost trebled during the period <br>December 2011 to October 2014, increasing from 908,600 to 2,645,593.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-11-21T14:52:56.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155971/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155971/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","101 Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the cost of calling the 101 non-emergency number on use of the number.","false","Biography information for Cathy Jamieson","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Cathy Jamieson","214673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155972","Home Office","false","2014-11-26","<p>It is long-standing policy not to discuss specific information held on UN or EU Travel Ban Lists implemented by the UK that is not in the public domain as to do so would not be in the interests of border and national security.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-26T15:22:38.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155972/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155972/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155972/answer/previousversion/28888","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155972/answer/previousversion/28888","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many individuals on the UK sanctions list are not on the UK travel ban list.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","214605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155973","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>UKVI customer service standards are to assess all visitor applications within 15 working days and all settlement applications within 60 working days, and the UKVI operation in Pretoria continues to meet these customer service standards, including for Malawian applications.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T15:59:56.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155973/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155973/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Entry Clearances: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the average length of time taken between first application for and being granted a UK visa for applications from Malawi in each month since June 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","214575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155974","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The Home Office does not retain this data. However, it is important to note that visa fees are non-refundable after a customer has submitted the application and provided biometric details, as at this point we have commenced assessment of the application. Currently, 86% of applications submitted in Malawi are successful.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T14:55:59.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155974/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155974/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Entry Clearances: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of how much money her Department received from (a) successful and (b) unsuccessful visa applications from Malawi in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","214573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155975","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The Home Office has pursued this consolidation programme in order to improve the quality of its operations, as well as to realise savings for the taxpayer. Globally, savings have been realised, for example, in areas such asreduced estates costs, more streamlined support services, and lower staff numbers. It is not possible to disaggregate the Home Office savings associated with consolidation in one post or one region.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T14:34:11.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155975/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155975/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Visas: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the money saved by her Department by the move to regional hubs in Africa to process UK visa applications.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","214574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155976","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>It is not possible to answer the questions without incurring disproportionate costs as the data relating to litigation expenditure is not held in a format that allows us to answer the question.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","214621","2014-11-25T14:36:01.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155976/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155976/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost of asylum application appeals was in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","214622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155977","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-20","<p /> <p>Lady Justice Macur’s Review is entirely independent of Government and its timetable is a matter for her . She is on record as saying that her Review would be thorough and that she would not draw any conclusions until she had considered all the evidence. I am, however, confident that good progress has been made and the Review is nearing its completion. The Government looks forward to receiving Lady Justice Macur’s Report next year.</p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes",,"2014-11-20T17:42:19.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155977/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155977/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-17","Child Abuse in North Wales Judicial Inquiry Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he expects that the Macur Review will report.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","214637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155978","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>It is not possible to answer the questions without incurring disproportionate costs as the data relating to litigation expenditure is not held in a format that allows us to answer the question.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","214622","2014-11-25T14:36:01.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155978/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155978/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost was of legal representation in asylum claims in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","214621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155979","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<blockquote><p>The table below shows the number of asylum appeal applications and determinations in each of the last five years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><strong>Asylum appeal applications and determinations, 2009 to 2013 (1)(2)(3)</strong></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>Year</strong></td><td><strong>Appeals received</strong></td><td><strong>Total appeals determined</strong></td><td><strong>Appeals allowed</strong></td><td><strong>% appeals allowed</strong></td><td><strong>Appeals dismissed</strong></td><td><strong>Appeals withdrawn</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2009</strong></td><td><strong>14,340</strong></td><td><strong>12,813</strong></td><td><strong>3,712</strong></td><td><strong>29%</strong></td><td><strong>8,627</strong></td><td><strong>474</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2010</strong></td><td><strong>13,928</strong></td><td><strong>14,723</strong></td><td><strong>4,029</strong></td><td><strong>27%</strong></td><td><strong>10,061</strong></td><td><strong>633</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2011</strong></td><td><strong>9,986</strong></td><td><strong>10,597</strong></td><td><strong>2,779</strong></td><td><strong>26%</strong></td><td><strong>7,139</strong></td><td><strong>679</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2012</strong></td><td><strong>8,197</strong></td><td><strong>8,285</strong></td><td><strong>2,208</strong></td><td><strong>27%</strong></td><td><strong>5,472</strong></td><td><strong>605</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2013</strong></td><td><strong>8,519</strong></td><td><strong>8,325</strong></td><td><strong>2,078</strong></td><td><strong>25%</strong></td><td><strong>5,681</strong></td><td><strong>566</strong></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="3">(1) Figures for 2013 are provisional.</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="7">(2) HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) (formerly the Tribunals Service Immigration and Asylum (TSIA)), consists of the First-tier Tribunal and Upper Tribunal of the Immigration and Asylum Chamber (FTTIAC and UTIAC). This replaced the Asylum and Immigration Tribunal (AIT) on 15 February 2010. All figures for appeals determined are cases dealt with by Immigration Judges at the AIT or FTTIAC.</td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="8">(3) Withdrawn figures include cases withdrawn by the Home Office, as well as those withdrawn by the appellant.</td></tr></tbody></table></blockquote><p> </p><p><br>These figures are regularly published in the quarterly and annual statistics on asylum appeal applications and determinations, within Immigration Statistics: April – June 2014, published by the Home Office on the GOV.UK website: <br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T16:07:43.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155979/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155979/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many and what proportion of asylum application decisions were overturned on appeal in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","214623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155980","Home Office","false","2014-12-09","<p>The table below shows the number of asylum initial decisions for main applicants in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="10"><strong>Grant rates for asylum, humanitarian protection, discretionary leave or other grants of stay for main applicants, 2009 to 2013(1)(2)</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Year</td><td>% Granted</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2009</strong></td><td>28%</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2010</strong></td><td>26%</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2011</strong></td><td>33%</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2012</strong></td><td>36%</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><strong>2013</strong></td><td>37%</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="3">(1) Figures for 2013 are provisional.</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="5">(2) Granted include grants of asylum, humanitarian protection, discretionary leave, leave to remain under family life or private life rules, leave outside the rules and UASC leave.</td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-12-09T15:03:22.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155980/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155980/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of claims for asylum were successful in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","214624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155981","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>With over 3.2 million Syrian refugees now in Syria’s neighbouring countries, the Government believes that humanitarian aid and actively seeking to end the conflict are the most effective ways for the UK to help the majority of those <br>displaced, rather than large scale resettlement. We have made our position on this clear in relevant discussions with international partners and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). We are aware that states have <br>responded to the crisis in different ways; it is right that the international community should consider all available means to relieve the suffering of Syrians displaced by the conflict. <br><br>To complement our humanitarian aid, we operate the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme to relocate the most vulnerable displaced Syrians who cannot be supported effectively long term in the region to the UK. The scheme is <br>based on need rather than fulfilling a quota; however, we expect it to help several hundred people over three years. This is in addition to our consideration of asylum claims lodged in the UK under our normal rules. However, we strongly believe that we should continue to focus on aid rather than resettlement as the best way for the UK to maximise our impact, and we therefore have no current plans to expand the scheme.<br><br>I am pleased to confirm that Karen Pierce, Ambassador and Permanent Representative, UK Mission to the UN and Other International Organisations, Geneva will represent the UK at the UNHCR Global Resettlement Pledging Conference on 9 December 2014.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T14:33:42.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155981/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155981/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Asylum: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had on UNHCR's request for more resettlement places for Syrian Refugees in 2015-16; if she will make it her policy to expand the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme ahead of UNHCR's global pledging conference in December 2014; and whether she or another Minister will attend that conference.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","214593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155982","Home Office","false","2014-11-27","<p>The Home Office provides support to local authority for Prevent activity based on an assessment of risk, to ensure that they understand the threat of extremism and are equipped to deal with it effectively. We currently fund 30 priority areas, plus an additional 14 areas which receive Home Office support for Prevent initiatives, but do not have a funded Prevent co-ordinator as in priority areas. Crawley is one of the additional areas. <br><br>Since June 2011 the Home Office has funded over 180 Prevent local authority projects. These include activity on education, internet safety, and families – all projects now address the risk of travel to Syria and Iraq in different ways. £40 million has been allocated for Prevent spending in 2014/15.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-27T16:45:02.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155982/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155982/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what projects her Department is sponsoring to tackle radicalisation  leading to violent extremism in (a) Crawley and (b) nationally.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","214426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155983","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The requested information is not available. A subset of the latest published figures show that as at 30 June 2014 there were 294 female people detained in Yarl’s Wood immigration removal centre who had been held in the immigration estate for less than 6 months, 9 for between 6 and 12 months and none for longer.<br><br>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of people detained in the United Kingdom for immigration purposes, within Immigration Statistics: April – June 2014, from the GOV.UK website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T16:06:09.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155983/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155983/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many women have been detained at Yarl's Wood Detention Centre for (a) 0 to six months, (b) six to 12 months, (c) over one year and (d) two years or more.","false","Biography information for Alistair Burt","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","214450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155984","Home Office","false","2014-11-20","<p>We have no plans to introduce new regulations at this stage. Gold, unlike scrap metal such as lead, is sold through many different outlets including antique shops, jewellers, pawnbrokers and shops offering cash for goods. Any new regulation would potentially be both complex and expensive to implement and enforce. <br><br>The crime prevention panel that we have set up in the Home Office is looking at new ways to prevent the theft of gold. This includes a review of an existing voluntary code of practice on the sale of gold that has been developed by police in collaboration with the National Pawnbrokers Association, the British Jewellers’ Association, the National Association of Goldsmiths and others. <br>Shops signing up to this code of practice agree to follow a number of guidelines, including asking for proof of identity when gold is offered for sale and maintaining detailed records of goods purchased. We expect this work to be completed in early 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-11-20T16:58:13.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155984/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155984/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Metals: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will bring forward proposals for the introduction of a legal requirement for verification of suppliers' identity, similar to that included in the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013, for gold and jewellery.","false","Biography information for Stephen Mosley","City of Chester","Stephen Mosley","214478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155985","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>It has been estimated that an estate of around 5,000 beds will support the removal of those with no right to remain in the UK. This figure is subject to reviews of demand, affordability and value for money.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T14:32:30.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155985/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155985/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Detention Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many spaces are required in the immigration detention estate.","false","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","214477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155986","Home Office","false","2014-11-27","<p>Prior to General Purpose Force training, the Home Office worked closely with the Ministry of Defence and Foreign Office on planning for the vetting and selection of trainees and, along with the Libyan command and supervisory team, on contingency planning for indiscipline. We worked closely with the Ministry of Defence, Foreign Office, Libyan command and supervisory team, Police and the Defence Section of the Libyan embassy to address trainee behaviour concerns and take appropriate action, including withdrawing trainees who failed to meet the expected standard of behaviour and performance.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-27T16:32:51.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155986/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155986/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Armed Forces: Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions her Department has had with the (a) Ministry of Defence and (b) Foreign and Commonwealth Office on constraining and restricting the undisciplined behaviour of Libyan personnel on Bassingbourn base; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","214475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155987","Department of Health","false","2014-11-24","<p>As at 23:59 on 17 November, a total of 931 passengers had been assessed at ports with enhanced screening operations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-24T17:33:15.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155987/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155987/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people have been screened for the Ebola virus in the UK following the recent implementation of screening procedures.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","214464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155988","Department of Health","false","2014-11-24","<p>Enhanced screening operations are in place at London Heathrow, London Gatwick, Birmingham and Manchester airports, and London St Pancras train station. Entry screening at these ports is estimated to cover 97% of through ticketed arrivals from affected countries.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Other ports of entry are covered remotely when Border Force notify of passengers travelling to the United Kingdom on indirect flights. Similarly, ships are met at ports when we have been informed of their arrival in advance, and they have docked in a country of interest within the last 21 days.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-24T17:32:47.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155988/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155988/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, where screening for the Ebola virus is taking place in the UK.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","214465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155989","Department of Health","false","2014-11-24","<p>Anyone flying from an affected country in West Africa is subject to exit screening overseen by the World Health Organization, which prevents those with symptoms consistent with Ebola from flying. All those who are assessed at screening in the United Kingdom as being at high risk because of their exposure history are asked to monitor their temperature twice daily and report this on a daily basis to the local health protection team for 21 days from the date they left a country of interest (currently Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone). Those who are considered at low risk are asked to monitor their temperature twice daily and report any rise in temperature to their local health protection team. As requested, local health protection teams will also follow up with particular individuals.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-24T17:31:27.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155989/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155989/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-17","West Africa: Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what procedures beyond initial screening exist to ensure that people entering the UK from West Africa are not carrying the Ebola virus.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","214463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155990","Home Office","false","2014-11-28","<p>Following the tragic incident at Tilbury, 34 individuals have claimed asylum and their cases are currently being considered. The UK has a proud history of granting asylum to those who need our protection and every claim will be considered on its individual merits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-28T16:43:53.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155990/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155990/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155990/answer/previousversion/28890","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155990/answer/previousversion/28890","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Asylum: Afghanistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of the Afghan asylum seekers found in a shipping container at Tilbury Docks in August 2014 have (a) been granted asylum, (b) been refused asylum but remain in the UK and (c) been refused asylum and removed from the UK.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","214513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155991","Home Office","false","2014-12-05","<p>There are no Malawi nationals on the UN and EU travel bans that are implemented by the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-12-05T16:29:44.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155991/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155991/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155991/answer/previousversion/28887","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155991/answer/previousversion/28887","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Travel Restrictions: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Malawi nationals are on the UK travel ban list.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","214520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155992","Home Office","false","2014-11-26","<p>It is long-standing policy not to discuss specific information held on UN or EU Travel Ban Lists implemented by the UK that is not in the public domain as to do so would not be in the interests of border and national security.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-26T15:22:12.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155992/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155992/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155992/answer/previousversion/28885","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155992/answer/previousversion/28885","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether any person on the UK sanctions list has travelled to the UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","214518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155993","Home Office","false","2014-12-05","<p>There are no Ethiopian nationals on the UN and EU travel bans that are implemented by the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-12-05T16:28:27.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155993/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155993/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155993/answer/previousversion/28886","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155993/answer/previousversion/28886","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Travel Restrictions: Ethiopia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Ethiopian nationals are on the UK travel ban list.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","214519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155994","Home Office","false","2014-11-21","<p>I am pleased to confirm that Karen Pierce, Ambassador and Permanent Representative, UK Mission to the UN and Other International Organisations, Geneva will represent the UK at the UNHCR Global Resettlement Pledging <br>Conference on 9 December.<br><br>With over 3.2 million Syrian refugees now in Syria’s neighbouring countries, the Government believes that humanitarian aid and actively seeking to end the conflict are the most effective ways for the UK to help the majority of those <br>displaced, rather than large scale resettlement. We have made our position on this clear in relevant discussions with international partners and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). We are aware that states have <br>responded to the crisis in different ways; it is right that the international community should consider all available means to relieve the suffering of Syrians displaced by the conflict. However, we strongly believe that we should continue to focus on aid rather than resettlement as the best way for the UK to maximise our impact. <br><br>To complement our humanitarian aid, we operate the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme to relocate the most vulnerable displaced Syrians who cannot be supported effectively long term in the region to the UK. This is in <br>addition to our consideration of asylum claims lodged in the UK under our normal rules.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","214610","2014-11-21T14:38:35.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155994/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155994/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","UN High Commissioner for Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to attend the UNHCR Global Resettlement Pledging Conference on 9 December 2014.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","214608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155995","Home Office","false","2014-11-26","<p>UK Visas and Immigration has moved to an application and payment process in which almost all customers apply and pay for their visas online. This system is already fully operational in Malawi. The move to online applications and <br>payments has delivered a streamlined process that is consistent with a wider global trend for online transactions and payments. Customers who do not have a credit or debit card can seek a sponsor to pay online. Prepaid credit or debit cards from the major suppliers can be provided by Malawian banks and used with this system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-26T15:21:41.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155995/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155995/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Entry Clearances: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the system for online applications for UK visas from Malawi will become fully operational.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","214572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155996","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold the data requested.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T14:32:00.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155996/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155996/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Entry Clearances: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of how many online applications for UK visas from Malawi have been started but remain uncompleted since December 2013.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","214571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155997","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The UKVI operation in Pretoria maintains a complaints register and can confirm that no customers have contacted officials in Pretoria directly from Malawi to complain about the online application process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T14:30:59.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155997/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155997/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Entry Clearances: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many complaints her Department has received about the system for online applications for UK visas from Malawi in each month since December 2013.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","214570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155998","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold the data requested in the format required. To obtain it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-25T16:02:29.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155998/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/155998/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-17","Entry Clearances: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the proportion of Malawians visiting the UK with a visa and at the invitation of a UK-based organisation who have (a) absconded and (b) engaged in criminal activity while in the UK in each month since June 2010.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","214569"
